          "body": "Verse 5 introduces the chapter's central theological claim: Assyria is 'the rod of My anger, and the staff in whose hands is My indignation.' God commissioned Assyria against a 'godless nation' (v. 6), meaning unfaithful Judah. The empire is the instrument of divine discipline. But the instrument has its own agenda: 'it is its purpose to destroy and to cut off many nations' (v. 7). Here lies the chapter's great theological tension — God uses a power that does not intend to serve Him, whose motivations are pure imperial ambition. The Assyrian king's monologue (vv. 8-14) is the most detailed expression of human hubris in the prophets. The boast runs from the comparison of conquered cities (v. 9) to the theological claim that Jerusalem's God is no different from the idols he has already demolished (vv. 10-11), to the crowning assertion: 'By the power of my hand and by my wisdom I did this' (v. 13). The response of verse 15 is one of the Old Testament's supreme rhetorical moments: does the axe boast over the one who chops with it? Does the saw exalt itself over the one who wields it? The tool's claim to autonomy is not merely arrogant — it is a categorical absurdity. God is Craftsman; Assyria is tool; and the tool will be judged for forgetting the difference."
