          "title": "The remnant — grace through decreed destruction (10:20-23)",
          "body": "The eschatological pivot at verse 20 ('in that day') introduces one of Isaiah's most theologically freighted passages. The remnant of Israel will do two things that the nation as a whole had failed to do: they will stop relying on Assyria (the foreign power they had courted as protection) and they will 'truly rely on the Lord, the Holy One of Israel.' The word 'truly' (*emet*) is significant — not nominal, not formal, not coerced, but genuine reliance. The name at verse 21 — 'the remnant of Jacob will return to the mighty God' (*El Gibbor*) — is the same divine title given to the Messiah in Isaiah 9:6. The remnant returns not merely to Yahweh in general but to the Mighty God who is also the coming child-king. Yet the promise is hedged with sobriety: though Israel is like the sand of the sea, only a remnant will return. The Abrahamic promise of numerical greatness (Genesis 22:17) does not guarantee universal participation. Destruction is decreed, and it 'overflows with righteousness' (v. 22) — the judgment is not regrettable excess but morally precise execution. Paul quotes verses 22-23 in Romans 9:27-28 to ground his argument that the ethnic composition of Israel has never been the criterion for belonging to the true Israel."
